    <DIV0>
        <HEADING>Biography</HEADING>
        <STANDARD WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES">Shields, Carol</STANDARD>
        <DIV1>
            <PERSONNAME>
                <DIV2>
                    <DATASTRUCT>
                        <DATAITEM>
                            <BIRTHNAME WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES">
                                <GIVEN>Carol</GIVEN>
                                <GIVEN>Ann</GIVEN>
                                <SURNAME>Warner</SURNAME>
                            </BIRTHNAME>
                        </DATAITEM>
                        <DATAITEM>
                            <MARRIED WROTEORPUBLISHEDAS="WROTEPUBLISHEDASYES" REG="Shields, Carol"
                                >Shields</MARRIED>
                        </DATAITEM>
                    </DATASTRUCT>
                </DIV2>
            </PERSONNAME>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>Birth and Background</HEADING>
            <BIRTH>
                <DIV2>
                    <CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="SYS">
                        <DATE CALENDAR="NEWSTYLE" CERTAINTY="CERT">2 June 1935</DATE>
                        <CHRONPROSE>
                            <BIRTHPOSITION POSITION="YOUNGEST">Carol Ann Warner (later CS) was born
                                at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Oak Park</SETTLEMENT>,
                                        <REGION>Illinois</REGION><GEOG REG="USA"/></PLACE>, the
                                youngest in a family of three children. She had one sister and one
                                brother.</BIRTHPOSITION>
                        </CHRONPROSE>
                        <BIBCITS>
                            <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"/>
                            <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 39" DBREF="60927">39</BIBCIT>
                        </BIBCITS>
                    </CHRONSTRUCT>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>It was an easy birth. CS hated it as a child when her mother used to tell
                            her she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">just slipped out like a lump of
                                butter.</QUOTE>
                            <BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 54" DBREF="60927">54</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </BIRTH>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <CULTURALFORMATION>
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>She was born into the <NATIONALITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="American"
                                >mid-American</NATIONALITY>
                            <RACECOLOUR SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" FOREBEAR="FAMILY">white</RACECOLOUR>
                            <CLASS SOCIALRANK="MANAGERIAL" SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES">middle
                                class</CLASS>, with <NATIONALHERITAGE FOREBEAR="MOTHER"
                                SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Swedish">immigrant
                                experience</NATIONALHERITAGE> only a couple of generations back in
                            her family. Neither of her parents had finished college, but they
                            counted on their children to rise in the world through education.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 38, 39" DBREF="60927">38, 39</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS> CS became <NATIONALITY SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="Canadian"
                                >Canadian</NATIONALITY> through marriage and residence.</P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
                <RELIGION>
                    <DIV2>
                        <SHORTPROSE>
                            <P>CS's family was church-going, <DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES"
                                    REG="Methodist"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church"
                                        >Methodist</ORGNAME></DENOMINATION>. For a while she
                                attended a <DENOMINATION SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES"
                                    REG="Society of Friends"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Society of Friends"
                                        >Quaker</ORGNAME></DENOMINATION> meeting, but by the 1980s
                                she described herself as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><DENOMINATION
                                        SELF-DEFINED="SELFYES" REG="agnostic"
                                        >notreligious</DENOMINATION></QUOTE>.<BIBCITS>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 38, 50" DBREF="60927"
                                        >38,50</BIBCIT>
                                </BIBCITS></P>
                        </SHORTPROSE>
                    </DIV2>
                </RELIGION>
            </CULTURALFORMATION>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <LOCATION RELATIONTO="LIVED">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P><PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Oak Park</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Illinois"/><GEOG
                                    REG="USA"/></PLACE>, where CS was raised, had associations with
                                <NAME>Ernest Hemingway</NAME>, but while CS was growing up there it
                            was a middle-class suburb of
                                    <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Chicago</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Illinois"
                                    /><GEOG REG="USA"/></PLACE>, entirely WASP (white Anglo-Saxon
                            Protestant). She later described it as like <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">living in
                                a paper bag.</QUOTE>
                            <BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 38" DBREF="60927">38</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </LOCATION>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <FAMILY>
                <MEMBER RELATION="MOTHER">
                    <DIV2>
                        <HEADING>Parents</HEADING>
                        <SHORTPROSE>
                            <P>Her mother, born <NAME STANDARD="Warner, Inez">Inez Selgren</NAME>,
                                was of Swedish origin. She had been a <JOB>teacher</JOB>, but did
                                not work while her children were young. She died in 1971.<BIBCITS>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 38" DBREF="60927">38</BIBCIT>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"/>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Shields, Small prelims" DBREF="60994"
                                        >prelims</BIBCIT>
                                </BIBCITS></P>
                        </SHORTPROSE>
                    </DIV2>
                </MEMBER>
                <MEMBER RELATION="FATHER">
                    <DIV2>
                        <SHORTPROSE>
                            <P>Her father, <NAME>Robert E. Warner</NAME>, <JOB REG="manager">managed
                                    a candy company</JOB>. CS later said she regretted the fact that
                                her family communicated so little among themselves.<BIBCITS>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 38" DBREF="60927">38</BIBCIT>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"/>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Colvin" DBREF="61346"/>
                                </BIBCITS></P>
                        </SHORTPROSE>
                    </DIV2>
                </MEMBER>
            </FAMILY>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>Education</HEADING>
            <EDUCATION MODE="SELF-TAUGHT">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>Always <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">a book-oriented kid,</QUOTE>
                            <BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 39" DBREF="60927">39</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS> Carol Warner (later CS) read everything she could find and
                            loved it all, including the old-fashioned children's books that had
                            belonged to her parents. Among the adult books that she met first were
                                    <TEXT><NAME>Betty Wehner Smith</NAME>'s <TITLE
                                    TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Tree Grows in Brooklyn</TITLE></TEXT>
                            and works by <TEXT><NAME>Edna Ferber</NAME></TEXT>.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 40" DBREF="60927">40</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </EDUCATION>
            <EDUCATION MODE="INSTITUTIONAL">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>After highschool in <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Oak Park</SETTLEMENT><REGION
                                    REG="Illinois"> </REGION><GEOG REG="USA"> </GEOG></PLACE> (where
                            every one of the 750 students in her graduating class was white), she
                            attended the conservative, undemanding <SCHOOL INSTITUTION="PRIVATE"
                                INSTITUTIONLEVEL="POST-SECONDARY" REG="Hanover College"
                                RELIGIOUS="RELIGIOUSYES"><ORGNAME STANDARD="Hanover College">Hanover
                                    College</ORGNAME></SCHOOL>, where most of her attention was
                            given to boys and dances. A year abroad at <SCHOOL STUDENTBODY="CO-ED"
                                INSTITUTIONLEVEL="POST-SECONDARY" REG="University of Exeter"
                                RELIGIOUS="RELIGIOUSYES"><ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Exeter"
                                    >Exeter University</ORGNAME></SCHOOL>, <PLACE><SETTLEMENT
                                    REG="Exeter"> </SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Devon"> </REGION><GEOG
                                    REG="England">UK</GEOG></PLACE>, was a revelation of something
                            different. Her tutor tore up the daily grade-sheet provided by Hanover,
                            and to her astonishment students sat around <SUBJECT REG="literature"
                                >talking about books</SUBJECT> in their spare time. She met her
                            future husband at Exeter, but nevertheless returned to Hanover to finish
                            her <DEGREE>BA</DEGREE>, which was awarded in 1957.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 38, 41-2" DBREF="60927"
                                    >38,41-2</BIBCIT>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"> </BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                        <P>Later she took advantage of her position as a faculty wife to enroll for
                            a course in <SUBJECT REG="creative writing">writing for
                                magazines</SUBJECT> (at her husband's suggestion) at the <SCHOOL
                                STUDENTBODY="CO-ED" INSTITUTIONLEVEL="POST-SECONDARY"
                                REG="University of Toronto" RELIGIOUS="RELIGIOUSYES"><ORGNAME
                                    STANDARD="University of Toronto">University of
                                Toronto</ORGNAME></SCHOOL>—which changed the direction of her
                            life—and then, in the 1970s, for an <DEGREE>MA in <SUBJECT>Canadian
                                    Literature</SUBJECT></DEGREE> at the <SCHOOL STUDENTBODY="CO-ED"
                                INSTITUTIONLEVEL="POST-SECONDARY" REG="University of Ottawa"
                                RELIGIOUS="RELIGIOUSYES"><ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Ottawa"
                                    >University of Ottawa</ORGNAME></SCHOOL> (awarded in 1975), with
                            a thesis on <NAME>Susanna Moodie</NAME>.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 42, 43" DBREF="60927">42, 43</BIBCIT>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"> </BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS> At Ottawa her graduate adviser told her: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">We
                                have not had much success with part-time, married women.</QUOTE> (It
                            was 1969, just before the influx of such women, who were to achieve
                                <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">enormous success</QUOTE>.) CS finished this degree
                            in 1975, after dropping out for a while to write.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 44, 45" DBREF="60927">44, 45</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </EDUCATION>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>Married Life</HEADING>
            <FAMILY>
                <MEMBER RELATION="HUSBAND">
                    <MARRIAGE>
                        <DIV2>
                            <CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE"
                                RESP="IMG">
                                <DATE CALENDAR="NEWSTYLE" CERTAINTY="CERT">20 July 1957</DATE>
                                <CHRONPROSE>
                                    <NAME STANDARD="Shields, Carol">Carol Warner</NAME> married
                                        <NAME>Donald Hugh Shields</NAME>, a <JOB REG="engineer"
                                        >civil engineer</JOB> who later <JOB REG="academic">taught
                                        engineering as an academic subject</JOB>.</CHRONPROSE>
                                <BIBCITS>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"/>
                                    <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Colvin" DBREF="61346"/>
                                </BIBCITS>
                            </CHRONSTRUCT>
                            <SHORTPROSE>
                                <P>She had met him while he was a <SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY
                                        PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEER="PHILANTHROPYVOLUNTEERYES">graduate
                                        student</SIGNIFICANTACTIVITY> at the University of Exeter in
                                    England. He was a Canadian from
                                            <PLACE><REGION>Saskatchewan</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"
                                        /></PLACE>. They got married after her graduation, <CHILDREN
                                        NUMBER="5">and she had her first baby, her son John, the
                                        next year. At this stage her only ambition was to be a
                                        mother and homemaker. She had four more children (<NAME
                                            STANDARD="Giardini, Anne">Anne</NAME>, <NAME
                                            STANDARD="Shields, Catherine">Catherine</NAME>, <NAME
                                            STANDARD="Shields, Margaret">Margaret</NAME>, and <NAME
                                            STANDARD="Shields, Sara">Sara</NAME>), and by the time
                                        of her death had ten grandchildren.<BIBCITS>
                                            <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 37, 42" DBREF="60927">37,
                                                42</BIBCIT>
                                            <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"/>
                                            <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Colvin" DBREF="61346"/>
                                        </BIBCITS></CHILDREN></P>
                            </SHORTPROSE>
                        </DIV2>
                    </MARRIAGE>
                </MEMBER>
            </FAMILY>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <LOCATION RELATIONTO="MOVED">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>CS began married life in a little apartment in
                                    <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Vancouver</SETTLEMENT><REGION
                                    REG="British Columbia"/><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE> (wondering
                            fleetingly why it was she who did all the cooking). Her husband's career
                            as doctoral student and then as faculty member took her to
                                    <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Toronto</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"
                                    /><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, back to
                                    <PLACE><GEOG>England</GEOG></PLACE>, and then to
                                    <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Ottawa</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Ontario"
                                    /><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>. By 1990 she was living in
                                    <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Winnipeg</SETTLEMENT>,
                                    <REGION>Manitoba</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, but after
                            she and her husband retired they moved to
                                    <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Victoria</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION>British
                                    Columbia</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"/></PLACE>, where she spent
                            the end of her life in a new, large, beautiful house.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 44, 42, 43, 37" DBREF="60927">44, 42,
                                    43, 37</BIBCIT>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Colvin" DBREF="61346"/>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </LOCATION>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <OCCUPATION>
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>While studying for her MA, CS began working at home as <JOB>editorial
                                assistant</JOB> on a scholarly quarterly, <EMPLOYER><TITLE
                                    TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Canadian Slavonic Papers</TITLE></EMPLOYER>.
                            She held this position from 1972 to 1974. She <JOB REG="academic"
                                >taught</JOB> at the <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME
                                    STANDARD="University of Ottawa">University of
                                Ottawa</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER> after doing her MA there, and then,
                            already a published writer, held a post as professor of English at the
                                    <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Manitoba">University
                                    of Manitoba</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER> until 2000. She was <JOB
                                REG="university chancellor">Chancellor</JOB> of the
                                    <EMPLOYER><ORGNAME STANDARD="University of Winnipeg">University
                                    of Winnipeg</ORGNAME></EMPLOYER>, 1996-2000.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Wachtel 45" DBREF="60927">45</BIBCIT>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"/>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Clark 23" DBREF="61347">23</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </OCCUPATION>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <FRIENDSASSOCIATES>
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>CS, who had said that in the 1960s she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">knew no
                                writers,</QUOTE> became a personal friend of her fellow author
                                <NAME>Alice Munro</NAME>, who called her (according to
                                <NAME>Margaret Atwood</NAME>) <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">just a luminous
                                person.</QUOTE>
                            <BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood 28" DBREF="61345" QTDIN="QTDINYES"
                                    >28</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </FRIENDSASSOCIATES>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <HEADING>Illness and Death</HEADING>
            <HEALTH ISSUE="PHYSICAL">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>Shields was diagnosed with breast cancer in 1998. Though she underwent a
                            mastectomy followed by chemotherapy, the cancer re-appeared in her liver
                            in 2000.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Colvin" DBREF="61346"/>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="O'Malley" DBREF="62588"/>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CBC News Online" DBREF="63786"/>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </HEALTH>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <LOCATION RELATIONTO="TRAVELLED">
                <DIV2>
                    <SHORTPROSE>
                        <P>She made a visit to England during the period of remission.<BIBCITS>
                                <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Atwood 28" DBREF="61345" QTDIN="QTDINYES"
                                    >28</BIBCIT>
                            </BIBCITS></P>
                    </SHORTPROSE>
                </DIV2>
            </LOCATION>
        </DIV1>
        <DIV1>
            <DEATH>
                <DIV2>
                    <CHRONSTRUCT RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RESP="SYS">
                        <DATE CALENDAR="NEWSTYLE" CERTAINTY="CERT">16 July 2003</DATE>
                        <CHRONPROSE>CS died of secondary <CAUSE>breast cancer</CAUSE> in
                                    <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Victoria</SETTLEMENT>, <REGION
                                    REG="British Columbia">BC</REGION><GEOG REG="Canada"
                            /></PLACE>.</CHRONPROSE>
                        <BIBCITS>
                            <BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="CA" DBREF="16185"/>
                        </BIBCITS>
                    </CHRONSTRUCT>
                </DIV2>
            </DEATH>
        </DIV1>
